Azerbaijan plans to spend $7.2
billion on state investment projects this year, down from last
yearâ€™s $7.5 billion, President  Ilham Aliyev  said.  The budget funds were allocated to transportation,
 information technology , tourism, energy, irrigation and other
projects last year, Aliyev told a Cabinet meeting yesterday,
according to the state news agency Azartac.  Total investment in 2011 grew 13.6 percent to $20 billion
from the previous year. Of this, $13 billion were domestic and
$7 billion foreign investments, Aliyev said.  Eonomic Development Minister Sahin Mustafayev said the non-
oil economy accounted for $15.7 billion of the total investment
last year. Loans of $1.7 billion were signed with international
financial institutions to fund transportation, energy,
telecommunications, agriculture and social projects.  To contact the reporter on this story:
